<subSubSection id="C9350B0B72D6FDD0C7EF59CD295AFC8E" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="750AB10DD454C1AD4E9B46C8DF64DC80" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BB74D1472AA1F9BA6D97F0426C54DFB9" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
Until the present work, all 
<taxonomicName id="D56B026B2C42A20E5E90BCCD84F00E3C" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Vanenga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Vanenga" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Vanenga</taxonomicName>
specimens have been treated as 
<taxonomicName id="7F95424095F53968D2E21C3D645459D0" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Vanenga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Vanenga mera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mera">Vanenga mera</taxonomicName>
in the literature and various worldwide collections, but external and genital morphology, as well as biogeography, clearly separates the genus into two well-distinct species, with the name 
<taxonomicName id="C8E6216FEC100BB46C9D30B7DFD56250" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Vanenga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Vanenga mera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mera">Vanenga mera</taxonomicName>
only being applicable to the rarely collected Amazonian species. In 
<bibRefCitation id="2CF60CB817292EB074C38EFA37AC88F4" author="Schaus, W" editor="Seitz, A" journalOrPublisher="A. Kernen, Stuttgart" pageId="14" pageNumber="103" pagination="635 - 672" title="Familie Mimallonidae." volumeTitle="Die Gross-Schmetterlinge der Erde. 6. Die amerikanischen Spinner und Schwaermer" year="1928">
<normalizedToken id="482223AE22E6B97B31EFFA5A87DBE49C" originalValue="Schaus’s">Schaus's</normalizedToken>
(1928)
</bibRefCitation>
treatment of 
<taxonomicName id="CAB05056DFFA71E8EA6AD4DF149AC3F6" family="Mimallonidae" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" rank="family">Mimallonidae</taxonomicName>
, he considered all populations to be this one species; hence his records for Southeastern Brazil and Paraguay can be attributed to the following new species, now formally described below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
